          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              And the inevitable proof comes in: if you wipe your hard drive in the face of an RIAA suit, <A HREF="http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/2006/08/where-defendant-wiped-hard-drive-in.html" TARGET=_blank>expect things to go badly for you</A>.<BR><BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">In <I>Arista v. Tschirhart</I>, in San Antonio, Texas, the judge awarded judgment to the RIAA because the defendant -- in violation of a court order directing her to produce her computer's hard drive for inspection -- had the hard drive "wiped" first, thus deleting song files that had been downloaded. </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Now Ms. Tschirhart gets to wait while the RIAA decides exactly how much of an ass-reaming they want to inflict on her.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
