        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by AfroBoy:<BR>Out of curiosity, how can they prove you've downloaded songs purely from inspecting your HD?  How do they know you didn't just rip them all from CD, then lose all the CDs? <img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="Big Green" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::bigdumbgrin:--> <BR><BR>On the HD do they just need the songs themselves to proceed with legal action or do they need P2P software logs as well?<BR><BR>EDIT: Just read my post and these are silly questions, as they already have internet logs, which is how they would've caught her in the first place.  Now they just want to cure the cement shoes by finding the actual files.<BR><BR>Nothing to see here people. </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Actually there is something to see: the question of "how do they know [x]" is a good one.<BR><BR>First, a quick correction: the RIAA is trying to prove uploading (or, rather, distribution), not downloading. AFAICS, the evidence they intend to show in order to prove these cases is threefold:<BR><BR>1) A P2P app username linked to a publicly accessible, shared folder containing a number of songs for which they hold the copyright.<BR>2) The defendant's name/address linked to a particular ISP account that used the IP address associated with the above username.<BR>3) Evidence of the songs on the defendant's hard drive.<BR><BR>So their reasoning seems to be, "Defendant == username and the existence of these files in a shared folder == distribution."<BR><BR>Obviously there are immediate problems with this reasoning, e.g. Does the mere existence of files in a shared folder, absent proof that any were actually distributed == distribution? However, AFAIK none of these cases have yet reached the point at which the quality of this evidence can be discussed. Thus far, almost all of them have been settled, a few have been dismissed/withdrawn, and a few more are still in the process and may yet garner a final ruling that takes into account all of the evidence.<BR><BR>Until that point it's all varying degrees of speculation, unfortunately.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
