        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              A few things:<BR><BR>1) As a normal part of civil litigation, you have an affirmative duty to preserve any relevant materials from the moment you get the complaint (in some states, the obligation may arise before that, as soon as you get a whiff that you're about to get sued).<BR><BR>2) Tampering with HDs in an attempt to thwart discovery is dumb.  Law firms are employing technical consultants who are just as smart as you and are getting paid a lot of money to figure out stuff like that.  If you fuck up one little thing, like leaving the meta-data in a Word file indicating that a letter dated 2003 was somehow created last week, you're screwed.<BR><BR>3) "Losing" or "accidentally wiping" your HD will end in the same result -- the court will make every negative inference about the possible contents of the drive.  If the RIAA says "We think you downloaded 50-gazillion songs," you won't even be allowed to refute that assertion.<BR><BR>4) The court can issue serious fines if it decides that you purposefully tampered or destroyed evidence.  The big OMFG horror story going around now is the Morgan Stanley case, in which they got hit with a $1.5 billion default judgment (including $850 million in punitives) because it completely botched its electronic discovery obligations.  Let's just say that around the country defense attorneys are crossing every 't' and dotting every 'i' when it comes to preserving evidence, and plaintiffs' attorneys are salivating at the thought that some schmuck is going to try to pull a fast one.<BR><BR>So yeah, don't get cute.  Maybe half the time you can get away with it.  The other half you'll get caught and have your ass handed to you.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
