        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              That might get you slapped with obstruction of justice or contempt of court or some such charge.  This is a civil case, but disobeying the judge, including by destroying evidence or perjury, can get you in criminal trouble.<BR><BR>I know of several psychology and sociology researchers who have done time for refusing to reveal their sources to the justice dept. in that doing so would get them arrested for drug dealing, prostitution and the like.  One case in particular, the DoJ siezed their laptop, but all the files were heavily encrypted.  They wouldn't give the information away, and got a token sentence.  Moral of the story, if you don't give the court access to the information they want, they have ways of making your life unpleasant.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
