            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by meldroc:<BR>You've gotta be more clever when wiping your hard drive...<BR><BR>First, you wipe your hard drive with DBAN (Darik's Boot and Nuke at <A HREF="http://dban.sourceforge.net/)" TARGET=_blank>http://dban.sourceforge.net/)</A> to ensure that even the NSA couldn't recover traces of your P2P usage.<BR> </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR><img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_rolleyes.gif" alt="Roll Eyes" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::rolleyes:--><BR>You don't honestly believe that do you? If they really want it they'll get it.<BR>I read a whitepaper a while ago sayhing the only real way to completely destroy it is to grind up or completely melt the drive. This is the route the ultra paranoid .gov agencies take. Otherwise they can still pick up the residual signatures of anything that was there for any amount time. Something about flipping bits for a 1/1000sec doesn't completely flip the polarity and you can pick this up with high end instruments.<BR><BR>DBAN is only good against your average schmuck when geek squad forgets to "dispose" your old disk. For anyone else it is just a question of how much they want to spend.<BR><BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by raihanan:<BR>Hypothetical question:  what if she had encrypted the hard drive (or at least the folder with the mp3 files) prior to the subpoena.  For the sake of argument, let's say she does submit the HD as-is.  Would she be compelled to provide the password?  If so, could she plead the 5th on that? </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>Last I heard is that anything committed to physical media of any kind is fair game, encrypted or not. You can be forced to divulge a password for encrypted materials. Failure to do so will just land you in the slammer anyway, this time for contempt.<BR><BR>A possible way around this is to use something like truecrypt. The idea is to make a encrypted folder then encrypt it inside another encrypted folder which also contains honeypot data. Supposedly it fools them into thinking the extra freespace (1st encrypted folder) is just white noise. I don't think anyone has actually put this to any actual legal test though.<BR><BR>The only real privacy is in your head, and who knows how long that will last.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
